# Feature Discovery Protocol — MANDATORY

Before writing tests for ANY module, you MUST complete the Full Feature Inventory.
This prevents gaps in test coverage. Skipping this protocol is a **critical violation**.

---

## Root Cause Analysis: Why Features Get Missed

These failure modes cause real coverage gaps. Every rule below is derived from
actual mistakes made during test automation projects.

### Mistake 1: "User-Mentioned Bias"
The user says "test Documents, Notes, and Spreadsheets." You test exactly those
three and stop — even though Slides, Search, and Settings were all visible on
the same page.
**Rule:** NEVER limit scope to only what the user explicitly names. When told
"test Module X," that means **every feature inside Module X**.

### Mistake 2: "First-Scroll Blindness"
An item was the 4th card on a hub page, right next to the other 3. It was skipped
because exploration fixated on the first visible items.
**Rule:** When you land on a hub page, count and LIST every card, link, button,
and section BEFORE doing anything else.

### Mistake 3: "Smoke-Test-as-Complete Fallacy"
A smoke test verified a card EXISTS on the hub, but then the feature behind
that card was treated as "covered" with no dedicated tests.
**Rule:** A smoke test for a parent page does NOT count as coverage for child
features. If your smoke test checks that a link exists, you MUST follow it.

### Mistake 4: "Hub-Only Tunnel Vision"
Standalone apps connected to the module were missed because exploration only
looked at what was directly rendered on the hub page.
**Rule:** Discovery does not stop at the hub. Also check:
  - Sidebar navigation for related modules
  - Dev repo route definitions
  - Cross-module imports and links
  - "Create" menu in sidebar for item types

### Mistake 5: "Same-Shape Assumption"
Two sub-features were assumed to share the same editor layout. All tests
failed because the second feature had a completely different UI.
**Rule:** NEVER assume two sub-apps share the same layout. Always inspect
each feature's UI separately.

### Mistake 6: "Context-Menu Copy-Paste"
One item type uses "Pin/Unpin" while another uses "Add to favorites." These
differences were discovered only after tests failed.
**Rule:** Open the context menu for EACH item type individually and record
the exact menu items.

### Mistake 7: "No Enumeration Before Implementation"
Tests were written immediately after a brief look at the hub, before mapping
all features. Later features were missed due to momentum.
**Rule:** Produce a written coverage matrix BEFORE writing any code.

### Mistake 8: "First-Module-Gets-Gold, Rest-Gets-Bronze"
The first module received 12 comprehensive tests. Quality degraded with each
subsequent module — the last ones got only 5 tests.
**Rule:** After completing the first module, extract a **Test Parity Baseline**.
Every subsequent module must match it or document why a category doesn't apply.

### Mistake 9: "Smoke-Only Without Justification"
Some modules got only smoke tests with no E2E interaction tests. They were
marked "complete" with only visibility checks.
**Rule:** Smoke-only is ONLY acceptable with a documented technical blocker.
"It's complex" is NOT a valid blocker.

### Mistake 10: "Rule-Exists-But-Not-Executed"
The discovery protocol was documented but never actually followed. Tests were
written without any of the required gate artifacts.
**Rule:** The protocol is a **checklist to execute**, not a document to have.
Every phase MUST produce a visible output artifact.

### Mistake 11: "Delegating Without Protocol"
Work was delegated to sub-agents without sharing the discovery protocol.
The delegated work was incomplete.
**Rule:** When delegating, complete discovery first, include the coverage
matrix in the delegation, and audit output against the matrix.

### Mistake 12: "Locators Leaking Into Specs"
When adding "deeper" tests, raw locator calls were written directly in spec files,
violating the POM architecture.
**Rule:** EVERY assertion about a UI element MUST go through a Steps method.
Spec files must contain ZERO `page.locator()` calls.

---

## MANDATORY GATE SYSTEM

You CANNOT proceed to the next phase without producing the required gate artifact.

### GATE 1: ENUMERATION (before any code)
**Required output:** A numbered list of every discoverable feature, tab, button,
section, and interactive element for the module.
**Failure to produce:** STOP. You cannot write any page/steps/spec file.

### GATE 2: COVERAGE MATRIX (before any code)
**Required output:** A table mapping every discovered feature to its planned test
coverage (Smoke / E2E / N/A with reason).
**Failure to produce:** STOP. You cannot write any page/steps/spec file.

### GATE 3: POM COMPLIANCE CHECK (after writing code)
**Required output:** Verify zero raw locator calls exist in spec files.
If ANY `page.locator()` / `page.getByRole()` / `page.getByText()` found in specs,
move them to page objects + steps methods.

### GATE 4: PARITY TABLE (after all modules in a batch are done)
**Required output:** A comparison table showing every module vs every test category.
Every cell must be ✅ or N/A-with-reason. No `?` cells.

